---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ArticleSchema from '../../components/ArticleSchema.astro';
import FaqSection from '../../components/FaqSection.astro';
import { site } from '../../content';
const path = '/alternatives/attentive-alternative';
const title = 'Best Attentive Alternatives for Shopify SMS Marketing in 2026';
const desc = 'Compare Attentive alternatives for Shopify SMS by scale, consent operations, email coordination, message economics, and migration risk.';
const tools = [
  { name: 'Postscript', best: 'SMS-native Shopify cart and campaign work', pros: 'Focused SMS workflows and Shopify operations', cons: 'Email lifecycle may need a separate platform', price: 'Verify current messaging pricing', source: 'https://postscript.io/' },
  { name: 'Klaviyo', best: 'Deep email-and-SMS product behavior', pros: 'Rich Shopify events and cross-channel segmentation', cons: 'Profile cost and governance grow with complexity', price: 'Verify current contact and feature pricing', source: 'https://www.klaviyo.com/pricing' },
  { name: 'Omnisend', best: 'Accessible bundled email, SMS, and push', pros: 'Fast multichannel ecommerce workflows', cons: 'Channel costs and collision rules need monitoring', price: 'Verify current contact and channel pricing', source: 'https://www.omnisend.com/pricing/' },
  { name: 'Brevo', best: 'Broad email, SMS, and transactional coverage', pros: 'Several messaging jobs in one platform', cons: 'Shopify-specific event depth needs testing', price: 'Verify current send and channel pricing', source: 'https://www.brevo.com/pricing/' },
  { name: 'Sequenzy', best: 'Email lifecycle beside a specialist SMS sender', pros: 'Focused education, post-purchase, and winback sequences', cons: 'Not a direct SMS replacement', price: 'Verify current plan and integration coverage', source: 'https://sequenzy.io/' },
];
const faqs = [
  { question: 'Why consider an Attentive alternative?', answer: 'A store may need a smaller operating model, deeper email lifecycle, lower complexity, a different message-cost structure, or a deliberate split between SMS and email ownership.' },
  { question: 'Is Attentive only for enterprise brands?', answer: 'Fit depends on SMS volume, team capability, consent operations, and the value of managed scale. Smaller teams should test whether they will use the operational depth.' },
  { question: 'What should be preserved during migration?', answer: 'Preserve opt-in source and timestamps, opt-outs, quiet hours, phone attributes, exclusions, templates, and cross-channel collision rules.' },
];
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={desc} site={site} path={path}><ArticleSchema title={title} description={desc} siteName={site.name} domain={site.domain} path={path} /><main class="container py-14 md:py-20"><a href="/alternatives" class="link text-sm">← All alternatives</a><p class="badge mt-6">Shopify SMS strategy</p><h1 class="hero-title mt-5 max-w-5xl">{title}</h1><p class="mt-7 max-w-3xl text-xl leading-9 text-orange-950/80">Attentive alternatives should be judged by the SMS program the team can actually operate: consent, frequency, event fidelity, email coordination, and incremental margin after message costs.</p><section class="mt-12 max-w-5xl overflow-x-auto rounded-2xl border border-orange-950/15 bg-white"><table class="w-full text-left"><thead><tr><th>Platform</th><th>Best fit</th><th>Pros</th><th>Tradeoff</th></tr></thead><tbody>{tools.map((tool, i) => <tr class={i === 0 ? 'highlight-row' : ''}><td class="font-semibold">{tool.name}</td><td>{tool.best}</td><td>{tool.pros}</td><td>{tool.cons}</td></tr>)}</tbody></table></section><article class="prose-shopify mt-14 max-w-4xl"><h2>Measure SMS as an incremental channel</h2><p>SMS attribution can look strong when it reaches customers who were already likely to purchase. Compare incremental orders, margin after discounts, opt-outs, complaints, and email collisions. Platform-reported revenue is evidence to investigate, not a guaranteed causal lift.</p><p>Map message classes before switching: cart urgency, shipping or service, replenishment, product launch, and winback. Each needs different timing, consent, and suppression rules.</p><h2>Platform notes</h2>{tools.map((tool, i) => <section><h3>{i + 1}. {tool.name}</h3><p><strong>Best for:</strong> {tool.best}. <strong>Pros:</strong> {tool.pros}. <strong>Cons:</strong> {tool.cons}. <strong>Pricing:</strong> {tool.price}. Review the <a href={tool.source} target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">official source</a> and include message volume, carrier fees, contacts, seats, and integration work.</p><table><tbody><tr><th>Consent test</th><td>Can the team prove opt-in, honor STOP, enforce quiet hours, and preserve exclusions?</td></tr><tr><th>Incrementality test</th><td>Can the team compare message-driven outcomes with a reasonable baseline or holdout?</td></tr></tbody></table></section>)}<h2>Migration checklist</h2><ol><li>Export consent evidence, opt-outs, timestamps, source, quiet hours, segments, templates, and live flows.</li><li>Map Shopify product, cart, order, subscription, and service events to each message class.</li><li>Assign ownership for SMS compliance and cross-channel suppression.</li><li>Test cart, post-purchase, replenishment, and winback paths with an opt-out case.</li><li>Launch gradually and monitor incremental orders, margin, opt-outs, complaints, and collisions.</li></ol><h2>Verdict</h2><p>Choose Postscript for SMS-native Shopify work, Klaviyo for deep cross-channel behavior, Omnisend for accessible multichannel operations, Brevo for broad messaging, and Sequenzy when email lifecycle should sit beside a specialist sender. Keep Attentive when its scale and operating depth are genuinely used.</p></article><FaqSection faqs={faqs} title="Attentive alternatives FAQ" /><p class="mt-12 text-orange-950/75">Continue with <a class="link" href="/apps">app profiles</a>, <a class="link" href="/compare">comparisons</a>, and <a class="link" href="/guides">SMS operator guides</a>.</p></main></BaseLayout>
